---
import BrowserSupport from "../components/BrowserSupport.astro";
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
---

<p-slide class="cover-internal">
  <h1>Modern color</h1>

  <PNotes>
    <p>This is where "runtime" gets visceral — colors people can see.</p>
    <p>Frame: we used to precompute every shade. Now the browser does it.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h3 class="main-gradient">Beyond hsl</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      🌀 <span>hsl lightness </span><span class="main-sub-gradient">lies</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      👁️ <span class="main-sub-gradient">oklch</span><span>
        is perceptually uniform</span
      >
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      🎚️ <span>Same L = </span><span class="main-sub-gradient"
        >same perceived lightness</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      The concrete example: hsl(60 100% 50%) yellow and hsl(240 100% 50%) blue
      have the same "lightness" number but look wildly different.
    </p>
    <p>oklch fixes that — L actually maps to what the eye sees.</p>
    <p>
      If asked: oklab is the cartesian form, oklch the polar one. Same space.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">oklch — lightness, chroma, hue</span> 🎨
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="oklch.css">
    <code is:raw class="language-scss">
    button {
        /* L: 0-1 · C: intensity · H: 0-360 */
        color: oklch(0.7 0.15 250);
    }
 
    /* a balanced ramp — L changes, C is softened at the edges */
    --c-100: oklch(0.95 0.05 250);
    --c-500: oklch(0.70 0.15 250);
    --c-900: oklch(0.40 0.15 250);</code>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Point at the ramp: only the L channel moves, hue and chroma are stable.
    </p>
    <p>That's why oklch ramps look even — impossible to do reliably in hsl.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<BrowserSupport
  feature="oklch"
  chrome="111"
  firefox="113"
  safari="15.4"
  status="All evergreen browsers"
/>

<p-slide b-a>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Shades</span> — compiled at build 🧪
  </h5>
  <div class="cols">
    <div p-effect="from left">
      <p class="tag">
        Before — <span class="main-sub-gradient">compiled at build</span>
      </p>
      <pre
        class="small-line"
        data-label-file="button.scss">
        <code is:raw class="language-scss">
  $brand: #4060d0;

  button               { background: $brand; }
  button:hover         { background: darken($brand, 15%); }
  button[data-subtle]  { background: lighten($brand, 40%); } </code>
      </pre>
    </div>
  </div>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Before, shade generation usually happened before the CSS reached the
      browser.
    </p>
    <p>
      darken() and lighten() run once, at build time. The result is frozen in
      the shipped CSS.
    </p>
    <p>
      The intent is dynamic — derive a hover shade from the brand color — but
      the output is static.
    </p>
    <p>
      Then move to color-mix(): same intent, but computed live from one token.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">color-mix() — shades at runtime</span> 🧪
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="color-mix.css">
    <code is:raw class="language-scss">
    :root {
        --brand: oklch(0.7 0.15 250);
    }
 
    /* generate the ramp from ONE token, in the browser */
    button              { background: var(--brand); }
    button:hover        { background: color-mix(in oklch, var(--brand), black 15%); }
    button[data-subtle] { background: color-mix(in oklch, var(--brand), white 80%); }</code>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>This is the slide that kills the Sass color functions.</p>
    <p>
      One source token, every shade derived live. Change --brand and the whole
      ramp follows — no rebuild.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mention the interpolation space matters: "in oklch" keeps mixes clean.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<BrowserSupport
  feature="color-mix()"
  chrome="111"
  firefox="113"
  safari="16.2"
  status="All evergreen browsers"
/>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Relative color — derive from a base</span> ♻️
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="relative-color.css">
    <code is:raw class="language-scss">
    :root {
        --brand: oklch(0.7 0.15 250);
    }
 
    /* take --brand apart and rebuild it, channel by channel */
    [data-muted]   { color: oklch(from var(--brand) l c h / 0.5); }

    [data-lighter] { color: oklch(from var(--brand)
                      clamp(0, calc(l + 0.2), 1) c h); }

    [data-neutral] { color: oklch(from var(--brand) l 0 h); }</code>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      "from var(--brand)" destructures the color into l / c / h you can reuse.
    </p>
    <p>Walk the three: alpha, lighter via calc on L, desaturated via C = 0.</p>
    <p>
      This + color-mix is a full palette system with zero build-time color
      tooling.
    </p>
    <p>We need clamp L in lighter, because calc(l + 0.2) can go over 1.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<BrowserSupport
  feature="Relative color"
  chrome="131"
  firefox="133"
  safari="18"
  status="~90% global coverage"
/>

<p-slide b-a>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">Dark mode</span> — duplicated blocks 🌗
  </h5>
  <div class="cols">
    <div p-effect="from left">
      <p class="tag">
        Before — <span class="main-sub-gradient">duplicated block</span>
      </p>
      <pre
        class="small-line"
        data-label-file="theme.css">
        <code style="font-size: 0.55em" is:raw class="language-scss">
        article {
          background: white;
          color: black;
        }

        @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
          article {
            background: #1a1a1a;
            color: white;
          }
        }</code>
      </pre>
    </div>
  </div>

  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Before, dark mode often meant duplicating the same selector inside a media
      query.
    </p>
    <p>
      This works, but it scales badly: every themed property has to be declared
      twice.
    </p>
    <p>
      Miss one property and you can easily end up with a half-broken dark mode.
    </p>
    <p>Then move to light-dark(): one property, two values, declared inline.</p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h5 style="margin-block-end: 1em" class="center">
    <span class="main-gradient">light-dark() — dark mode in one line</span> 🌗
  </h5>
  <pre
    class="small-line"
    data-label-file="light-dark.css">
    <code is:raw class="language-scss">
    :root {
        color-scheme: light dark;
    }
 
    article {
        background: light-dark(white, oklch(0.2 0 0));
        color:      light-dark(black, white);
    }</code>
  </pre>

  <PNotes>
    <p>color-scheme is the gotcha — without it, light-dark() does nothing.</p>
    <p>
      No media query, no duplicated theme block, no JS toggle wiring for the OS
      preference.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<BrowserSupport
  feature="light-dark()"
  chrome="123"
  firefox="120"
  safari="17.5"
  status="All evergreen browsers"
/>
